What are Macros in C?
A macro in C is a piece of code defined using the #define preprocessor directive.
It is handled by the C Preprocessor before compilation.

👉 Macros are basically text substitution.

When the compiler sees a macro name, it replaces it with its defined value before compiling the program.

1️⃣ Object-like Macros (Simple Macros)
These are used to define constants.

Syntax:
#define NAME value
Example:
#include <stdio.h>
#define PI 3.14159

int main() {
    printf("Value of PI = %f", PI);
    return 0;
}
🔹 Here PI is replaced with 3.14159 before compilation.
🔹 No memory is allocated for PI.

Why use this instead of variable?
Faster (no memory)

No type checking

Used for constants

2️⃣ Function-like Macros
These look like functions but are not actual functions.

Syntax:
#define NAME(parameters) expression
Example:
#include <stdio.h>
#define SQUARE(x) (x * x)

int main() {
    int a = 5;
    printf("Square = %d", SQUARE(a));
    return 0;
}
👉 The compiler replaces:

SQUARE(a)
with:

(a * a)
⚠️ Important Problem (Macro Pitfall)
printf("%d", SQUARE(2+3));
Expands to:

(2+3 * 2+3)
Result = 11 ❌ (wrong)

Correct macro:

#define SQUARE(x) ((x) * (x))
Always use parentheses in macros!

3️⃣ Multi-line Macros
Used when writing multiple statements.

#define PRINT(x) \
    printf("Value: %d\n", x); \
    printf("Done\n");
\ means continuation of macro in next line.

4️⃣ Conditional Compilation Macros
Used for debugging and platform-specific code.

#define DEBUG

#ifdef DEBUG
    printf("Debug mode ON\n");
#endif
Other directives:

#ifdef

#ifndef

#if

#else

#elif

#undef

5️⃣ Special Predefined Macros
C provides built-in macros:

Macro	Meaning
__FILE__	Current file name
__LINE__	Current line number
__DATE__	Compilation date
__TIME__	Compilation time
Example:

printf("File: %s\n", __FILE__);
printf("Line: %d\n", __LINE__);
