Let’s go very slowly and clearly.

🔹 Why Do We Need \ in Multi-Line Macros?
In C, a macro normally ends at the end of the line.

Example:

#define A 10
After this line ends, macro definition is finished.

So if you write:

#define PRINT(x)
    printf("Value: %d\n", x);
    printf("Done\n");
❌ This is WRONG.

Because the preprocessor thinks:

#define PRINT(x)
is one complete macro (empty macro),
and the next lines are normal C code → which will cause error.

🔹 What Does \ Do?
The backslash \ tells the preprocessor:

👉 “This macro continues to the next line.”

So this:

#define PRINT(x) \
    printf("Value: %d\n", x); \
    printf("Done\n");
is treated as one single line internally.

It becomes:

#define PRINT(x) printf("Value: %d\n", x); printf("Done\n");
🔹 Complete Working Example
#include <stdio.h>

#define PRINT(x) \
    printf("Value: %d\n", x); \
    printf("Done\n");

int main() {
    PRINT(10);
    return 0;
}
🔹 What Happens During Preprocessing?
When compiler sees:

PRINT(10);
It replaces it with:

printf("Value: %d\n", 10);
printf("Done\n");
So final code becomes:

int main() {
    printf("Value: %d\n", 10);
    printf("Done\n");
    return 0;
}
Output:

Value: 10
Done
🔥 Important Problem With Multi-line Macros
If you use macro inside if:

if (1)
    PRINT(10);
It becomes:

if (1)
    printf("Value: %d\n", 10);
printf("Done\n");
⚠️ Now only first printf is inside if.
Second printf runs always.

That is dangerous.

🔹 Correct Professional Way (Very Important for Interviews)
We wrap multi-line macros inside do { } while(0):

#define PRINT(x) do { \
    printf("Value: %d\n", x); \
    printf("Done\n"); \
} while(0)
Now it behaves like a single statement.

🔹 Why do { } while(0)?
Because:

It groups multiple statements

It acts like one single statement

Safe inside if-else

🔥 Simple Understanding
Without \ → macro ends at line
With \ → macro continues to next line

Think of \ as:

"Don’t stop here, continue macro definition."

